  "original_lang": "si",
  "original_title": "\u2019\u2019\u0da9\u0d9c\u0dca\u0dbd\u0dc3\u0dca \u0db8\u0dd4\u0db1\u0dca\u0dbb\u0ddd\u2019\u2019 \u0d9a\u0ddc\u0dc5\u0db9 \u0db6\u0dbd\u0dcf \u0db4\u0dd2\u0da7\u0dad\u0dca \u200c\u0dc0\u0dd9\u0dba\u0dd2",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Douglas Munro leaves for Colombo",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "The P627 deep sea attack ship, which was officially handed over to the Sri Lanka Navy by the United States Coast Guard Department, left yesterday (03) from Seattle Port in America for its new home port, Colombo Port, the Navy said.",
        "The US Coast Guard Ship Douglas Munro, which belonged to the United States Coast Guard Department, was handed over to the Navy on October 26, 2021, and after being modernized to suit the operational needs of the Sri Lankan Navy, it has started traveling to Melesha Colombo. .",
        "After the official handover, this ship has joined the Sri Lanka Navy fleet under the pennant number P627, and it is scheduled to be assigned to the authority after its arrival in the country.",
        "According to the Navy, the second ship belonging to the Hamilton Class High Endurance Cutter class is 115 meters long and has a maximum speed of 29 nautical miles per hour.",
        "The Navy says that this ship is capable of carrying out invasion operations covering a distance of at least 14000 nautical miles at one time, and is equipped with modern technical devices and facilities that can carry out operations with a total of 187 ships.",
        "This ship P 627 is scheduled to arrive at the port of Colombo in the first week of November 2022 after a long voyage of nearly two months.",
        "In order to strengthen and develop the partnership in order to overcome the common maritime challenges in the ocean region, the deep sea surveillance ships Sri Lanka Naval Ship Samudura \"P 621\" and Sahigajabahu \"P 626\" have been given by the US Coast Guard Department to the Sri Lanka Navy. The Navy also says that this is the third ship given to the Sri Lankan Navy by the US Coast Guard Department with the aim of further developing that partnership.",
        "On that journey to Sri Lanka, to provide supplies and service needs, the ports of Honolulu in America, Apraga ports in Guam in America, Manila ports in the Philippines and Changi ports in Singapore are scheduled to be called."
      ],
